<h1>Problem 1812 - 2014 USA TST, P6 of 6, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 8</h2>
<p>For a prime \(p\), a subset \(S\) of residues modulo \(p\) is called a sum-free multiplicative subgroup of \(\mathbb F_p\) if
<ol><li>there is a nonzero residue \(\alpha\) modulo \(p\) such that \(S = \left\{ 1, \alpha^1, \alpha^2, \dots \right\}\) (all considered mod \(p\)), and</li><li>there are no \(a,b,c \in S\) (not necessarily distinct) such that \(a+b \equiv c \pmod p\).</li></ol>
Prove that for every integer \(N\), there is a prime \(p\) and a sum-free multiplicative subgroup \(S\) of \(\mathbb F_p\) such that \(\left\lvert S \right\rvert \ge N\).</p>
